The '''Archer artillery system''', or '''Archer – FH77BW L52''', or '''''Artillerisystem'' 08''', is a Swedish [[self-propelled howitzer]] system.<ref>{{Cite web |title=ARCHER: The development of wheeled artillery with a new purpose |url=https://www.baesystems.com/en/feature/archer--the-development-of-wheeled-artillery-with-a-new-purpose |access-date=2 September 2022 |website=BAE Systems {{!}} International |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.regjeringen.no/nb/dep/fd/pressesenter/pressemeldinger/2007/Norsk-svensk-samarbeid-om-fremtidens-art.html?id=468611 |title=Norwegian-Swedish cooperation on the future of artillery – invitation to the signing of agreement|date=30 May 2007|publisher=[[Norwegian Ministry of Defence]] |language=Norwegian |access-date=30 March 2010}}</ref> The main piece of the system is a fully automated [[155 mm calibre|155 mm]] L52 (52-[[Caliber (artillery)#Barrel length|calibre]]-long) gun-[[howitzer]] and a [[M151 Protector]] remote-controlled weapon station mounted on a modified [[Six-wheel drive|6×6]] [[chassis]] of the [[Volvo Construction Equipment|Volvo]] A30D all-terrain [[articulated hauler]]. The crew and engine compartment is armoured and the cab is fitted with bullet and fragmentation-resistant windows. The system also includes an ammunition resupply vehicle, a support vehicle, [[Bofors/Nexter Bonus|BONUS]] submunitions,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baesystems.com/BAEProd/groups/public/documents/bae_publication/bae_pdf_bonus.pdf |title=155 BONUS Strike and destroy up to 35 km |work= BAE Systems- Bofors AB|date=3 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826121452/http://www.baesystems.com/BAEProd/groups/public/documents/bae_publication/bae_pdf_bonus.pdf |archive-date=26 August 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[M982 Excalibur]] guided projectiles.

The howitzer's superior attack range and exceptional maneuverability makes it ideal for [[counter-battery fire]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Sweden Reveals How Many People Engaged in Maintenance of Archer Artillery Systems |url=https://en.defence-ua.com/weapon_and_tech/sweden_reveals_how_many_people_engaged_in_maintenance_of_archer_artillery_systems-8571.html |date=15 November 2023}}</ref>

==Development==
The project began in 1995 as earlier studies for a self-propelled system based on the existing [[Haubits FH77|FH 77 howitzer]]. Further test systems received the designation FH 77BD and FH 77BW. By 2004, two prototypes had been ordered based on a lengthened version of the FH 77B mounted on a modified Volvo Construction Equipment A30D six-wheel drive articulated haul truck.

In September 2006, BAE Systems Bofors received a SEK 40 million contract from the FMV (Försvarets materielverk, [[Swedish Defence Materiel Administration]]) for detailed design work on the Archer program.

In 2008, Sweden ordered a first batch of seven units, while Norway ordered one.<ref name="kuriren12">{{cite web |last=Zerpe |first=Håkan |date=4 September 2008 |title=Klartecken för Archer |url=http://www.kuriren.nu/nyheter/klartecken-for-archer-4134401.aspx |access-date=28 December 2016 |publisher=}}</ref><ref name="milse12">{{cite web |title=Government decision on ARCHER |url=http://www.mil.se/en/News/News-milse/Government-decision-on-Archer/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207182631/http://www.mil.se/en/News/News-milse/Government-decision-on-Archer/ |archive-date=7 February 2009 |access-date=30 March 2010 |publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (Sweden)]]}}</ref> In August 2009, Norway and Sweden ordered 24 Archers each, in a cooperative deal.<ref name="milse22">{{cite web |date= |title=Archer FH77 BW L52 Self-Propelled Howitzer, Sweden |url=http://www.army-technology.com/projects/archerhowitzer/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110427150710/http://www.army-technology.com/projects/archerhowitzer/ |archive-date=27 April 2011 |access-date=30 April 2011 |publisher=army-technology.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=16 June 2022 |title=Sweden's Archer Self-Propelled Artillery Project |url=https://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/sweden-norway-to-cooperate-on-archer-artillery-project-05142/ |access-date=17 December 2023 |website=www.defenseindustrydaily.com/ |language=en}}</ref>

The howitzer was developed for the [[Swedish Armed Forces]] following a contract awarded to [[Bofors]] (now [[BAE Systems AB|BAE Systems Bofors]]) in 2003 by ''Försvarets Materielverk'' (FMV), the Swedish defence acquisition agency to build two demonstrator howitzers. The prototype FH77 BW L52 self-propelled howitzers entered firing trials in Sweden in 2005 and 2006. In September 2006, the FMV placed a contract for detailed design work on Archer and, in January 2007, a contract for the next development phase. The [[Swedish Army]] had a requirement for 24 systems (two battalions). In September 2008, the Swedish government approved the final development and procurement of the Archer artillery system.

In November 2008, Sweden and Norway signed a co-operative agreement for the development of the Archer system and, in January 2009, awarded BAE Systems a contract to complete development of the artillery system with the exception of the remote weapon system which is made by [[Kongsberg Defence & Aerospace]]. A final prototype was scheduled for completion by September 2009, which was expected to be followed by a contract for 48 systems – 24 for Sweden and 24 for Norway. Archer was planned to enter service in 2011 but was delayed until October 2013. This was because of unforeseen technical problems.<ref>{{cite news |last=Eriksson |first=Anna K |date=17 June 2013 |title=Sverige står helt utan artilleri |url=http://www.svd.se/nyheter/inrikes/sverige-star-helt-utan-artilleri_8272024.svd |access-date=28 December 2016 |newspaper=Svenska Dagbladet |publisher=}}</ref> It caused the Norwegian government to withdraw from the project in December 2013.<ref>{{cite web |date=6 December 2013 |title=Norge avslutter kontrakten om artillerisystemet Archer |url=https://www.regjeringen.no/no/aktuelt/norge-avslutter-kontrakten-om-artilleris/id747473/ |website=Regjeringen.no |language=no}}</ref>

The Swedish Army received its first four pre-serial production FH-77 BW L52 Archer systems on 23 September 2013,<ref>[http://www.armyrecognition.com/september_2013_defense_industry_military_news_uk/swedish_army_has_received_first_pre-serial_production_archer_155mm_6x6_self-propelled_howitzer_23091.html Swedish army has received first pre-serial production of Archer 155mm 6x6 self-propelled howitzer] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201204852/http://www.armyrecognition.com/september_2013_defense_industry_military_news_uk/swedish_army_has_received_first_pre-serial_production_archer_155mm_6x6_self-propelled_howitzer_23091.html |date=1 February 2019 }}. Armyrecognition.com, 23 September 2013</ref><ref>[http://www.deagel.com/news/Sweden-Takes-Delivery-of-First-Four-Archer-Artillery-Systems_n000011961.aspx Sweden Takes Delivery of First Four Archer Artillery Systems]. Deagel.com, 26 September 2013</ref> and the first guns finally entered service on 1 February 2016.<ref>[http://www.forsvarsmakten.se/en/news/2016/02/a-good-day-at-the-artillery-regiment/ A Good Day at the Artillery Regiment]. Forsvarsmakten.se, 9 February 2016</ref>

In 2019, a new configuration of the Archer, with the howitzer mounted on a [[Rheinmetall MAN Military Vehicles|Rheinmetall MAN]] [[RMMV HX range of tactical trucks|HX2 8×8 tactical truck]], was revealed. Sweden had ordered a number of HX2 trucks in 2014, with deliveries commencing in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Archer 155 mm - self-propelled gun-howitzer |url=http://www.military-today.com/artillery/archer.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080912041803if_/http://www.military-today.com/artillery/archer.htm |url-status=usurped |archive-date=12 September 2008 |access-date=24 October 2022}}</ref> On 23 January 2020, [[Janes Information Services]] reported that BAE Systems Bofors had begun trials for the HX2 variant.<ref>{{Cite web |title=BAE Systems Bofors begins trials for HX2-based Archer |url=https://www.janes.com/defence-news/news-detail/bae-systems-bofors-begins-trials-for-hx2-based-archer |access-date=24 October 2022 |website=Janes.com |date=23 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The first Archer of this configuration was delivered to FMV in April 2026.<ref>https://forsvarstidningen.se/nyheter/forsta-archer-8x8-levererad-till-fmv</ref>

==Design==

=== Vehicles ===

==== Operational vehicle platform – Volvo A30D ====
This vehicle platform is a modification of the [[Volvo A30D]] 6×6 articulated all-terrain hauler vehicle. It was developed for the first variant of the Archer artillery system. Operators control the entire gun system in any weather from the safety of the armoured vehicle cabin which is fitted with bullet and fragmentation-proof windows. The cabin seats up to four personnel. The howitzer is operated by three or four crew but can be run by a single operator.<ref name="BAEArcherProd" />

The system also includes a munition carrier consisting of a removable, modified standard container mounted on a ballistic-proofed all-terrain lorry. As per the agreement announced in March 2010, the contract to commence the serial production of 48 Archers was signed for US$200 million, resulting in a unit cost of US$4.17 million.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Sweden's Archer Self-Propelled Artillery Project – Defense Industry Daily |url=https://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/sweden-norway-to-cooperate-on-archer-artillery-project-05142/ |access-date=17 December 2023 |website=www.defenseindustrydaily.com/ |language=en}}</ref>

24 Archer were upgraded to the C-standard by November 2025. The upgrades improve the reliability of the system, and include a new command system. This upgraded variant is also compatible to be used on new platforms.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-11-02 |title=Sweden completes modernization of its Archer artillery |url=https://militaeraktuell.at/en/sweden-completes-modernization-of-its-archer-artillery/ |access-date=2026-01-14 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Hill |first=John |date=2025-10-31 |title=Sweden receives its last upgraded Archer artillery system |url=https://www.army-technology.com/news/sweden-receives-its-last-upgraded-archer-artillery-system/ |access-date=2026-01-14 |website=Army Technology |language=en-US}}</ref>

==== Future vehicle platform – Rheinmetall HX2 8×8 ====
The [[RMMV HX range of tactical trucks|Rheinmetall HX2 8×8]] (HX44M) is the second platform for which the Archer artillery system is being developed.<ref>{{Cite web |title=ARCHER: The development of wheeled artillery with a new purpose |url=https://www.baesystems.com/en/feature/archer--the-development-of-wheeled-artillery-with-a-new-purpose |access-date=2 November 2023 |website=www.baesystems.com}}</ref> The Swedish Army ordered 48 in September 2023 for US$500 million. The delivery is planned to start from 2025.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://defence-blog.com/sweden-orders-more-archer-wheeled-artillery-systems/|title=Sweden orders more ARCHER wheeled artillery systems}}</ref> There are no changes to the system mentioned other than its adaptation to the vehicle.<ref>{{Cite news |date=13 September 2023 |title=Sweden hands UK's BAE extra $500 million order for more artillery systems |url=https://www.reuters.com/markets/europe/sweden-hands-uks-bae-extra-500-mln-order-more-artillery-systems-2023-09-13/ |access-date=2 November 2023 |work=Reuters |language=en}}</ref> The first units were delivered to the Swedish FMV on 21 April 2026.<ref>https://nordicdefencesector.com/sv/article/fmv-receives-first-delivery-of-archer-8x8</ref>

==== Potential vehicle platform – Oshkosh defence trucks ====
BAE Bofors is proposing this system as an option to the US military, and concept variants based on the [[Heavy Expanded Mobility Tactical Truck|Oshkosh HEMTT]] (8×8) or the [[Palletized Load System|Oshkosh PLS]] (10×10).<ref>{{Cite web |title=ARCHER Mobile Howitzer |url=https://www.baesystems.com/en/product/archer |access-date=2 November 2023 |website=www.baesystems.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://defence-blog.com/bae-systems-offers-us-army-new-version-of-archer-howitzers/|title=BAE Systems offers US Army new version of Archer howitzers}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=AUSA 2023: New US chassis for Archer {{!}} Shephard |url=https://www.shephardmedia.com/news/landwarfareintl/ausa-2023-new-us-chassis-for-archer/ |access-date=2 November 2023 |website=www.shephardmedia.com |language=en}}</ref>

=== Ammunition ===
[[File:Artcher commons.JPG|thumb|Another view of a deployed Archer]]
The vehicle carries 21 155&nbsp;mm projectiles in a fully automatic magazine.<ref name=BAEArcherProd/> Reloading the magazine from the accompanying munitions carrier takes about 10 minutes using the purpose-built lifting device. The howitzer can use [[NATO]] modular charges or Bofors Uniflex 2 modular charges. The Uniflex 2IM modular charge system consists of two sizes of combustible charge cases; one full-size and one half-size case, both filled with the same type of [[Insensitive munition|insensitive]] [[guanylurea dinitramide]] (GuDN) propellant. The modular charge system allows several increments of charge to be available and increases the system's [[multiple rounds simultaneous impact]] (MRSI) capability and good range overlap between the increments. With BAE Bofors/Nexter BONUS rounds the range is {{convert|35|km|mi}}.  Due to the glide wings of the precision-guided [[Raytheon Technologies|Raytheon]]/Bofors [[M982 Excalibur]] rounds, the range of the gun is extended to more than {{convert|50|km|mi}}.<ref name=BAEArcherProd>{{cite web | title=Archer mobile howitzer|access-date=8 September 2022 |url=https://www.baesystems.com/en/product/archer |website=[[BAE Systems]]  |date=24 August 2022}}</ref> The Excalibur shell is corrected in flight towards a pre-programmed trajectory by a GPS guidance system.
For armoured vehicles, the Bofors 155 BONUS is used.

=== Operational capabilities ===
The system is designed for high strategic, operational and tactical mobility. The vehicle can reach road speeds of up to {{convert|90|km/h|mph}}, is capable of traversing snow up to a depth of {{convert|1|m|ft|spell=in}}, is rail transportable and can be air-transported in [[Boeing C-17 Globemaster III]] or [[Airbus A400M Atlas]] aircraft.<ref name="BAEArcherProd" /> A large hydraulically operated stabilizer is installed in the rear of the chassis and is lowered with the vehicle in the selected firing position. The gun elevation and traverse ranges are −1° to +70° vertically and −85° to +85° horizontally. The initial deployment time and the redeployment times are less than 30 seconds.<ref name="BAEArcherProd" /> The system provides precision strike and high sustained firepower for support and for deep firing operations with more than 25&nbsp;t of ammunition per gun and 24-hour operation. The howitzer has a continuous fire rate of 75 rounds per hour, an intensive fire rate of 20 rounds (i.e., a full magazine) in 2.5 minutes<ref name="BAEArcherProd" /> (effective rate, 480 rounds per hour), and a salvo fire rate of three rounds in 15 seconds (effective rate, 720 rounds per hour). The MRSI capability, multiple round simultaneous impact, is up to 6 rounds. Direct-sighting can be used for target ranges up to {{convert|2000|m|yd}}.

