== Operators ==
[[File:Archer Artillery System at Bold Quest 21.webm|250x250px|thumb|Swedish [[Artillery Regiment (2000)|Artillery Regiment]] (A 9) demonstrates the highly-mobile Archer artillery system on 15 November 2021, at [[Camp Atterbury]].]] [[File:Archer Artillery System.jpg|250x250px|thumb|An Archer Artillery System of the [[British Army]]'s [[19th Regiment Royal Artillery]] displayed in ready position for [[Battle of Cambrai (1917)|Cambrai Day]].]] [[File:Archer Operators.svg|250x250px|thumb|upright=1.8|{{legend|#0B60D4|Current operators}}]]

; {{flagicon|Sweden}} [[Swedish Army]] (26)
: Archer based on the Volvo A30D:
:* Purchases:
:** 24 Archer ordered in March 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Archer |url=https://www.fmv.se/armada/projekt/archer/ |access-date=2026-01-14 |website=www.fmv.se |language=sv}}</ref><ref name=":4">{{Cite web |last=admin |date=2014-01-20 |title=Sweden investigates Norway's withdrawal impact on Archer project |url=https://www.army-technology.com/news/newssweden-investigates-norways-withdrawal-from-archer-project-4162679/ |access-date=2026-01-10 |website=Army Technology |language=en-US}}</ref>
:** 24 Archer to be ordered, announced by the government in September 2016 (the 24 that were planned for Norway, but whom withdrew from the project in December 2013).<ref>{{Cite web |title=Archer FH77 BW L52 Self-Propelled Howitzer |url=https://www.army-technology.com/projects/archerhowitzer/ |access-date=2026-01-14 |website=Army Technology |language=en-US}}</ref>
:* Sales:
:** 14 Archer for the [[British Army]]: approval requested by the government to the [[Riksdag]] the 16 March 2023, which was accepted. The first Archer was delivered to the UK in October 2023.<ref name=":6">{{Cite press release |title=DE&S has delivered the first Archer wheeled artillery system to the British Army |date=6 October 2023 |publisher=[[Defence Equipment and Support]], [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] |url=https://des.mod.uk/des-has-delivered-the-first-archer-wheeled-artillery-system-to-the-british-army/ |access-date=14 July 2024 |author=<!--not stated-->}}</ref> The 14 were all delivered by July 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bisht |first=Inder Singh |date=28 February 2023 |title=UK Seeks Ukraine-Bound AS90 Artillery Replacement Within 12 Months |url=https://www.thedefensepost.com/2023/02/28/uk-as90-artillery-replacement/ |access-date=16 March 2023 |website=The Defense Post |language=en-US}}</ref>
:* Donations:
:** 8 Archer for the [[Ukrainian Ground Forces|Ukrainian Army]]: approval requested by the government to the [[Riksdag]] the 16 March 2023, which was accepted.<ref>{{Cite web |date=16 March 2023 |title=Sweden to send 8 Archer artillery systems to Ukraine |url=https://news.yahoo.com/sweden-send-8-archer-artillery-163337832.html |access-date=16 March 2023 |website=Yahoo News |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Råssjö |first=Pelle |date=2 November 2020 |title=Kanonglädje i Bofors – ska leverera fler Archer i försvarets nya satsning |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/orebro/utokade-forsvaret-ger-nya-order-till-bofors |access-date=16 March 2021 |work=[[Sveriges Television|SVT]] |language=sv}}</ref><ref name="aftonbladet 2023-03-162">{{Cite news |last=Wallberg |first=Peter |date=16 March 2023 |title=Nu klart: Ukraina får åtta Archer |url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/a/rl966l |access-date=16 March 2023 |work=[[Aftonbladet]] |location=Stockholm, Sweden |language=sv}}</ref> The 8 Archer were delivered to Ukraine by November 2023.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nyheter |first1=S. V. T. |date=3 November 2023 |title=Svenska Archer på plats i Ukraina |trans-title=Swedish Archer on the ground in Ukraine |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/snabbkollen/svenska-archer-pa-plats-i-ukraina--ltds6g |access-date=4 November 2023 |website=[[Sveriges Television|SVT]] |language=sv}}</ref><ref name="strategyPage2">StrategyPage [https://www.strategypage.com/htmw/htart/articles/20231201.aspx (1 Dec 2023) Artillery: Archer, Counterbattery and UAVs]</ref>
:* Status over time in the Swedish Army.
:** First batch deliveries: first 4 Archer delivered to the FMV in September 2013 (pre-serie)<ref>{{Cite web |date=26 September 2013 |title=First ARCHER systems delivered in Sweden |url=https://www.baesystems.com/en/article/first-archer-systems-delivered-in-sweden |access-date=2026-01-14 |website=www.baesystems.com}}</ref>, first serial produced Archer delivered in September 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |date=28 September 2015 |title=BAE Systems Delivers ARCHER Artillery System to Sweden |url=https://www.baesystems.com/en/article/bae-systems-delivers-archer-artillery-system-to-sweden |access-date=2026-01-14 |website=www.baesystems.com}}</ref> The initial batch of 24 Archer entered service between February 2016 and December 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Archer FH77 BW L52 Self-Propelled Howitzer |url=https://www.army-technology.com/projects/archerhowitzer/ |access-date=2026-01-14 |website=Army Technology |language=en-US}}</ref>
:** Deliveries of the second batch completed by November 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-11-26 |title=Swedish Army Receives Last Archer 155mm Self-propelled Howitzer from BAE Systems - MilitaryLeak.COM |url=https://militaryleak.com/2022/11/26/swedish-army-receives-last-archer-155mm-self-propelled-howitzer-from-bae-systems/ |access-date=2026-01-14 |language=en-US}}</ref>
:** March 2023: 24 in service. 24 in storage, among which 22 to be sold and donated, and 2 to be used by the [[Swedish Defence Materiel Administration|FMV]] to further develop the Archer artillery system.<ref name=":8">{{Cite web |date=16 March 2023 |title=Sweden to send 8 Archer artillery systems to Ukraine |url=https://news.yahoo.com/sweden-send-8-archer-artillery-163337832.html |access-date=16 March 2023 |website=Yahoo News |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=":9">{{Cite news |last=Råssjö |first=Pelle |date=2 November 2020 |title=Kanonglädje i Bofors – ska leverera fler Archer i försvarets nya satsning |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/orebro/utokade-forsvaret-ger-nya-order-till-bofors |access-date=16 March 2021 |work=[[Sveriges Television|SVT]] |language=sv}}</ref><ref name="aftonbladet 2023-03-163">{{Cite news |last=Wallberg |first=Peter |date=16 March 2023 |title=Nu klart: Ukraina får åtta Archer |url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/a/rl966l |access-date=16 March 2023 |work=[[Aftonbladet]] |location=Stockholm, Sweden |language=sv}}</ref>

; {{flagicon|UK}} [[British Army]] (14)
: 14 owned as of July 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bisht |first=Inder Singh |date=28 February 2023 |title=UK Seeks Ukraine-Bound AS90 Artillery Replacement Within 12 Months |url=https://www.thedefensepost.com/2023/02/28/uk-as90-artillery-replacement/ |access-date=16 March 2023 |website=The Defense Post |language=en-US}}</ref> On 16 March 2023, the Swedish Government asked for permission from the [[Riksdag]] to sell 14 Archer Artillery Systems to the British Army as an interim replacement for 32 [[AS-90]] gifted to Ukraine.<ref name="aftonbladet 2023-03-16">{{Cite news |last=Wallberg |first=Peter |date=16 March 2023 |title=Nu klart: Ukraina får åtta Archer |url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/a/rl966l |access-date=16 March 2023 |work=[[Aftonbladet]] |location=Stockholm, Sweden |language=sv}}</ref> Ownership of the systems was transferred in March 2023, and they would be fully operational by the following April.<ref name="des-mod 2023-03-16">{{Cite press release |title=British Army announces new artillery deal with Sweden |date=16 March 2023 |publisher=[[Defence Equipment and Support]], [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/british-army-announces-new-artillery-deal-with-sweden |access-date=16 March 2023 |author=<!--not stated-->}}</ref> The first Archer was delivered in October 2023<ref>{{Cite press release |author=<!--not stated--> |date=6 October 2023 |title=DE&S has delivered the first Archer wheeled artillery system to the British Army |url=https://des.mod.uk/des-has-delivered-the-first-archer-wheeled-artillery-system-to-the-british-army/ |publisher=[[Defence Equipment and Support]], [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] |access-date=14 July 2024}}</ref> and all were delivered by July 2024.<ref>[https://www.forces.net/technology/weapons-and-kit/british-armys-archer-arsenal-now-complete-arrival-10-more-howitzers British Army's Archer arsenal now complete with the arrival of 10 more howitzers]. ''[[Forces.net]]''. 16 July 2024.</ref>
; {{flagicon|Ukraine}} [[Ukrainian Ground Forces]] (8)
: Ukraine aid from Sweden:  
:* Archer based on the Volvo A30D
:** 8 Archer received as of November 2023.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nyheter |first1=S. V. T. |date=3 November 2023 |title=Svenska Archer på plats i Ukraina |trans-title=Swedish Archer on the ground in Ukraine |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/snabbkollen/svenska-archer-pa-plats-i-ukraina--ltds6g |access-date=4 November 2023 |website=[[Sveriges Television|SVT]] |language=sv}}</ref><ref name="strategyPage">StrategyPage [https://www.strategypage.com/htmw/htart/articles/20231201.aspx (1 Dec 2023) Artillery: Archer, Counterbattery and UAVs]</ref> On 16 March 2023, the Swedish government announced that it would send 8 Archer artillery systems to the Ukrainian armed forces.<ref name="aftonbladet 2023-03-16" />
:*Spare barrels:
:**10 pledged in July 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Regeringskansliet |first=Regeringen och |date=2025-07-03 |title=New purchases of defence materiel to Ukraine |url=https://www.government.se/press-releases/2025/07/new-purchases-of-defence-materiel-to-ukraine/ |access-date=2026-06-01 |website=Regeringskansliet |language=en}}</ref>

=== Systems under order ===
;{{flag|Sweden}} (84)
:All the new orders are based on the [[RMMV HX range of tactical trucks|Rheinmetall HX2 8×8]]. 
:;{{flagicon|Sweden}} [[Swedish Army]] (48)
:: 48 ordered under a contract signed in September 2023, with deliveries scheduled to begin in 2025.<ref name=":0">{{Cite press release |title=Försvarsmakten tillförs 48 nya Archerpjäser |date=13 September 2023 |publisher=[[Swedish Armed Forces|Försvarsmakten]] |url=https://www.forsvarsmakten.se/sv/aktuellt/2023/09/archer/ |access-date=13 September 2023 |author=<!--not stated-->}}</ref><ref name="bae-sep23-contract2">{{Cite press release |title=Sweden awards BAE Systems $500 million contract for additional 48 ARCHER artillery systems |date=13 September 2023 |publisher=[[BAE Systems]] |url=https://www.baesystems.com/en/article/sweden-awards-bae-systems-contract-for-additional-48-archer-artillery-systems |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230913215007/https://www.baesystems.com/en/article/sweden-awards-bae-systems-contract-for-additional-48-archer-artillery-systems |archive-date=13 September 2023 |author=<!--not stated-->}}</ref> The cost for 48 artillery systems was $500 million.<ref name="bae-sep23-contract2" />
:;{{flagicon|Ukraine}} [[Ukrainian Ground Forces]] (36)
::Aid packages from Sweden to the Ukrainian Ground Forces: 
::* 18 pledged in March 2025: The Swedish government authorised the [[Swedish Defence Materiel Administration|FMV]] to purchase 18 Archer systems to be supplied to Ukraine with deliveries starting in 2026.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Regeringskansliet |first=Regeringen och |date=13 March 2025 |title=New Swedish support strengthens Ukraine's artillery capacity |url=https://www.government.se/press-releases/2025/03/new-swedish-support-strengthens-ukraines-artillery-capacity/ |access-date=14 March 2025 |website=Regeringskansliet |language=en}}</ref>
::* 18 pledged in September 2025: The Swedish government decided on a 20th aid package, worth SEK 9.2 billion, that included a further 18 Archer artillery systems.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Regeringskansliet |first=Regeringen och |date=11 September 2025 |title=New military support package to Ukraine worth over SEK 9 billion |url=https://www.government.se/press-releases/2025/09/new-military-support-package-to-ukraine-worth-over-sek-9-billion/ |access-date=12 September 2025 |website=Regeringskansliet |language=en}}</ref>
;{{flagicon|Latvia}} [[Latvian Land Forces]] (18)
: On 11 June 2025, Latvian Minister of Defence [[Andris Sprūds|Andris Spruds]] announced that 18 Archer systems were to be acquired, based on the [[RMMV HX range of tactical trucks|Rheinmetall MAN HX2 8×8]] with deliveries starting in 2026.<ref>{{Cite web |date=11 June 2025 |title=Latvia to acquire 18 Archer self-propelled artillery systems from Sweden |url=https://defence-industry.eu/latvia-to-acquire-18-archer-self-propelled-artillery-systems-from-sweden/ |access-date=12 June 2025 |language=en}}</ref>
: The parliament approved the order in January 2026.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Purchase of Sweden's 'Archer' howitzers by Latvia rumbles forward |url=https://eng.lsm.lv/article/society/defence/13.01.2026-purchase-of-swedens-archer-howitzers-by-latvia-rumbles-forward.a629830/ |access-date=2026-01-14 |website=eng.lsm.lv |language=en}}</ref>
=== Potential operators ===

;{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Canadian Army]]
: Canada is considering the purchase of new artillery systems. On one side, a MLRS system system is considered, and on the other side, a lightweight mobile artillery platform is being looked at, among which the Archer is an option.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Belouizdad |first=Skander |date=2 May 2023 |title=As NATO allies grow impatient, Canada may be quietly planning major increase in defence spending: Richard Shimooka in the Hub |url=https://macdonaldlaurier.ca/as-nato-allies-grow-impatient-canada-may-be-quietly-planning-major-increase-in-defence-spending-richard-shimooka-in-the-hub/ |access-date=12 November 2024 |website=Macdonald-Laurier Institute |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=4 September 2024 |title=ON TARGET: CANADIAN ARMED FORCES: At the Tipping Point |url=https://www.espritdecorps.ca/on-target-4/on-target-canadian-armed-forces-at-the-tipping-point |access-date=12 November 2024 |website=espritdecorps |language=en-CA}}</ref>
; {{flagicon|ROM}} [[Romanian Land Forces]]
: BAE is offering the Archer for the Romanian Army, 36 wheeled self-propelled howitzers are planned to be ordered by Romania.<ref>{{Cite web |author=<!--not stated--> |date=24 May 2024 |title=BSDA 2024: BAE Systems to pitch AMPV, CV90, and Archer to Romania |url=https://www.janes.com/osint-insights/defence-news/land/bsda-2024-bae-systems-to-pitch-ampv-cv90-and-archer-to-romania |website=Janes |publisher=[[Janes Information Services]] |access-date=18 June 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |author=<!--not stated--> |date=11 July 2023 |title=S-a discutat producția în România a unor componente ale obuzierelor K9 Thunder. România demarează achiziția de obuziere autopropulsate |url=https://www.defenseromania.ro/s-a-discutat-productia-in-romania-a-unor-componente-ale-obuzierelor-k9-thunder-romania-demareaza-achizitia-de-obuziere-autopropulsate_623475.html |website=Defence Romania |language=ro |trans-title=Production of some components of the K9 Thunder howitzer in Romania under discussion. Romania begins to purchase self-propelled howitzers |access-date=14 July 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Dumitrache |first=Ciprian |date=31 May 2024 |title=Pentru România în viitor urmează și obuziere pe roți. Iar Archer ar putea fi integrat pe camioane Iveco produse aici, dar va fi concurență mare |url=https://www.defenseromania.ro/romania-vrea-si-obuziere-autopropulsate-pe-roti-archer-unul-din-posibilii-competitori-ar-putea-fi-integrat-pe-camioane-iveco-produse-in-tara_628492.html |website=Defence Romania |language=ro |trans-title=In the future, there will also be wheeled howitzers for Romania. And Archer could be integrated with Iveco trucks produced here, but there will be a lot of competition |access-date=18 June 2024}}</ref>
;{{flagicon|US}} [[US Army]]
: In July 2020, the [[United States Army|US Army]] released a request for proposals to evaluate wheeled self-propelled howitzers. In October 2020, BAE Systems offered the Archer as a participant to the RFP.<ref>{{Cite web |title=ARCHER wheeled howitzer offered for U.S. Army's 155 mm gun system |url=https://www.baesystems.com/en/article/bae-systems-offers-archer-wheeled-howitzer-for-us-army-155-mm-gun-system |access-date=3 January 2024 |website=www.baesystems.com}}</ref> The other platforms tested were the [[ATMOS 2000]], the [[CAESAR self-propelled howitzer|CAESAr]], the Brutus and the [[Nora B-52]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bisht |first=Inder Singh |date=12 January 2022 |title=US Army Seeking Next-Gen 155mm Truck-Mounted Howitzer |url=https://www.thedefensepost.com/2022/01/11/us-army-truck-mounted-howitzer/ |access-date=13 November 2023 |website=The Defense Post |language=en-us}}</ref> Throughout 2021, the various wheeled self-propelled howitzers conducted a shoot off evaluation at the Yuma Proving Ground in Arizona and at [[Camp Atterbury]]. The Archer was tested in November 2021.<ref>{{Cite web |last=admin |date=6 January 2022 |title=Swedish Armed Forces Demonstrates Archer Artillery System At Camp Atterbury, Indiana - MilitaryLeak.COM |url=https://militaryleak.com/2022/01/06/swedish-armed-forces-demonstrates-archer-artillery-system-at-camp-atterbury-indiana/ |access-date=3 January 2024 |website=militaryleak.com |language=en-US}}</ref> As part of the evaluation, [[Lieutenant General (United States)|Lieutenant General]] [[Erik C. Peterson (general)|Erik Peterson]], visited Sweden to inspect the system in April 2022.<ref>{{cite web |date=29 April 2022 |title=USA:s armé intresserad av att köpa svenskt artilleri |url=https://www.di.se/nyheter/usa-s-arme-intresserad-av-att-kopa-svenskt-artilleri/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Artilleripjäsen väcker USA:s intresse: "Kvalificerad kund" |url=https://www.tv4.se/artikel/7tIiEtoV2mWQPSxRVQtgy7/artilleripjaesen-som-vaecker-usa-s-intresse-en-kvalificerad-kund |website=www.tv4.se|date=4 May 2022 }}</ref>
: The interest for a wheeled self-propelled howitzer aims at increasing the mobility of the artillery capabilities, and to take a position between the [[M109 howitzer|M109]] and the [[M777 howitzer|M777]]. At the same time, the platforms tested would offer an artillery system with an increased range as the greatest operational calibre in the US Army is the 155mm L/39. The US Army ultimately did not move forward with acquiring a wheeled howitzer system.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Judson |first1=Jen |date=9 October 2023 |title=Change of plans: US Army embraces lessons learned from war in Ukraine |url=https://www.defensenews.com/land/2023/10/09/change-of-plans-us-army-embraces-lessons-learned-from-war-in-ukraine/ |access-date=16 October 2023 |website=defensenews.com}}</ref>
: At AUSA 2024, the US military mentioned its renewed interest for a wheeled howitzer under the ''"mobile tactical cannon"'' capability. The system will be selected in 2026, and a contract for a certain number of cannons is planned for 2027. The systems mentioned include the Archer and the [[RCH 155]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Judson |first=Jen |date=15 October 2024 |title=Why the Army is looking abroad to close a widening artillery gun gap |url=https://www.defensenews.com/land/2024/10/15/why-the-army-is-looking-abroad-to-close-a-widening-artillery-gun-gap/ |access-date=15 October 2024 |website=Defense News |language=en}}</ref>

=== Evaluation only ===

;{{flagicon|UK}} [[British Army]]
: The Archer system was one of the contenders for the British Army's ''Mobile Fires Platform'' programme. The variant offered was based on the Rheinmetall HX2 8×8 truck. As of December 2023, [[Babcock International|Babcock]] and [[Rheinmetall|Rheinmetall UK]] formally joined forces with [[BAE Systems AB|BAE Bofors]] to pitch the Archer to the British Army. Among the competitors, there were: [[CAESAR self-propelled howitzer|CAESAR]] ([[Nexter Systems|Nexter]]), the [[RCH 155|RCH-155]] ([[Krauss-Maffei Wegmann|KMW]]), the [[K9 Thunder]] ([[Hanwha Aerospace]]) and the ATI (Artillery Truck Interface, a module based on a HX3 10×10, made by [[Rheinmetall]]) which could eventually use a 155 L/60 calibre.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Chuter |first=Andrew |date=16 March 2023 |title=British Army buys 14 Archer howitzers to fill gap left by Ukraine aid |url=https://www.defensenews.com/land/2023/03/16/british-army-buys-14-archer-howitzers-to-fill-gap-left-by-ukraine-aid/ |access-date=13 November 2023 |website=Defense News |language=en}}</ref>
: In April 2024, a defence agreement was reached between Germany and the United Kingdom and the choice to purchase the [[RCH 155|RCH-155]] was made.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Allison |first=George |date=24 April 2024 |title=Britain to purchase Boxer-based RCH155 artillery systems |url=https://ukdefencejournal.org.uk/britain-to-purchase-boxer-based-rch155-artillery-systems/ |access-date=24 April 2024 |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=PM: UK and Germany open 'new chapter' in defence partnership |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/pm-uk-and-germany-open-new-chapter-in-defence-partnership |access-date=24 April 2024 |website=GOV.UK |language=en}}</ref>

=== Failed bid ===

;{{flagicon|SWI}} [[Swiss Armed Forces]]
: BAE Systems Bofors announced in June 2022 that Switzerland had shortlisted the Archer for the final round of its Future Artillery System competition "''Artillerie Wirkplattform und Wirkmittel 2026''".<ref>{{cite press release |title=BAE Systems' ARCHER 155mm mobile howitzer shortlisted by Swiss Armed Forces |date=10 June 2022 |publisher=BAE Systems |url=https://www.baesystems.com/en-us/article/bae-systems-archer-155mm-mobile-howitzer-shortlisted-by-swiss-armed-forces |access-date=14 July 2024}}</ref> The version selected is the one based on the [[RMMV HX range of tactical trucks|Rheinmetall HX2 8×8]]. On 11 August 2022, the Swiss [[Armasuisse|Federal Office for Defence Procurement]] confirmed this decision and announced that the Archer would compete against the [[RCH 155]]. One of the variant was based on the [[Boxer (armoured fighting vehicle)|Boxer]] platform and one based on the [[Mowag Piranha IV|Mowag Piranha IV 10×10]], and were evaluated in 2024.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Neues Artilleriesystem: Shortlist-Entscheid getroffen |date=11 August 2022 |publisher=[[Armasuisse]] |url=https://www.news.admin.ch/de/nsb?id=89927 |language=de |access-date=16 March 2023 |trans-title=New artillery system: Shortlist decision made |author=<!--not stated-->}}</ref>
: In November 2024, the Swiss Armed Forces selected the RCH-155 based on the [[Mowag Piranha IV|Mowag Piranha IV 10×10]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=5 November 2024 |title=Swiss Armed Forces selects AGM Artillery Gun Module from KNDS Deutschland |url=https://defence-industry.eu/swiss-armed-forces-selects-agm-artillery-gun-module-from-knds-deutschland/ |access-date=5 November 2024 |language=en}}</ref>

=== Cancelled order ===

; {{flagicon|Norway}} [[Norwegian Army]]
: 24 ordered for [[Artilleribataljonen|Royal Norwegian Artillery Battalion]]<ref name="SNC2">{{cite web |date=16 June 2022 |title=Sweden's Archer Self-Propelled Artillery Project |url=http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/Sweden-Norway-to-Cooperate-on-Archer-Artillery-Project-05142/ |access-date=28 December 2016 |website=Defense Industry Daily}}</ref> but the order was cancelled in December 2013 due to delays in the development and production, therefore not meeting needs within the time remaining available.<ref>[http://dmilt.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=8692:norway-mod-cancels-participation-in-swedish-archer-155mm&catid=1:europe&Itemid=57 Norway; Mod cancels participation in Swedish ARCHER 155mm] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20131211210323/http://dmilt.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=8692:norway-mod-cancels-participation-in-swedish-archer-155mm&catid=1:europe&Itemid=57|date=11 December 2013}}. Dmilt.com, 11 December 2013</ref> Norway later chose to purchase the [[K9 Thunder]] in December 2017.<ref>[https://www.defensenews.com/land/2017/12/20/norway-orders-k9-howitzers-in-latest-win-for-south-korean-arms-industry/ Norway orders K9 howitzers in latest win for South Korean arms industry]. ''[[Defense News]]''. 20 December 2017.</ref>

== Operational history ==

In January 2024, a Ukrainian documentary crew from [[United24]] observed the FH77BW Archer howitzer firing during combat missions. The news crew interviewed Ukrainian soldiers operating the system in the Luhansk region. One of the soldiers interviewed had previously worked with the Soviet-built [[152 mm gun-howitzer D-20|D-20 howitzer]]. In contrast to the towed D-20's manual operation the Ukrainian soldier praised the automation and rapid emplacement of the FH77BW, describing it as "Sniper Artillery" for its one shot - one kill ability.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Swedish Archer FH77BW L52 Howitzer in the Donetsk Region. Sniper Artillery in Action |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NbEvpXuNfCE |access-date=10 May 2024 |website=www.youtube.com| date=18 January 2024 }}</ref>

In February 2024, an Archer artillery system was hit by a Russian [[loitering munition]] close to the city of [[Kupiansk]]. Russian sources claimed that the howitzer was destroyed while Ukrainian sources claimed that the damage done to the vehicle was likely repairable.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Norbergh |first=Erik |date=24 January 2022 |title=Uppgifter: En svensk Archer förstörd i Ukraina – Senaste nytt om kriget i Ukraina |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/utrikes/direktrapport-forsamrat-sakerhetslage?inlagg=9fd68e51f3d90abd824eb5012b1b1ab4 |access-date=2 June 2024 |work=SVT Nyheter |language=sv}}</ref>

In March 2024, a reconnaissance unit of the Ukrainian [[63rd Mechanized Brigade (Ukraine)|63rd Mechanized Brigade]] detected multiple Russian D-20 howitzers near the city of [[Kreminna]]. The coordinates of the Russian howitzers was then passed on to the Ukrainian [[45th Artillery Brigade (Ukraine)|45th Artillery Brigade]] which performed counter-battery fire using an Archer artillery system, with drone footage showing the destruction of three D-20 howitzers.<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7OPLWSYB010 |title=Уражено 3 ворожі Д-20 артилеристами 45 ОАБр у взаємодії із аеророзвідкою 63 ОМБр. Східний напрямок |date=9 March 2024 |last=((45 окрема артилерійська бригада ЗСУ)) |access-date=2 June 2024 |via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Archer ACS destroyed enemy D-20 howitzers |url=https://mil.in.ua/en/news/archer-acs-destroyed-enemy-d-20-howitzers/ |access-date=2 June 2024 |website=Militarnyi |language=en-US}}</ref>

In May 2024, the Ukrainian 45th Artillery Brigade used the Archer system in combat during operations in the Luhansk region. The brigade's artillerymen, operating an FH77BW Archer howitzer successfully destroyed a Russian [[2S19 Msta-S]] self-propelled artillery system near the village of [[Chervonopopivka]]. The Russian gun had been spotted by a Ukrainian reconnaissance team and the destruction was verified by a [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drone]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ukrainian brigade destroys Russian artillery with cutting-edge Howitzer |url=https://essanews.com/ukrainian-brigade-destroys-russian-artillery-with-cutting-edge-howitzer,7024333182543489a |access-date=10 May 2024 |website=www.essanews.com|date=5 May 2024 }}</ref>

In 2025, the Swedish Army claimed Archer has challenges operating in subarctic terrain with deep snow and limited road infrastructure. Therefore, Sweden is looking for tracked howitzer to complement wheeled Archer artillery. The Army aims to establish two battalions equipped with [[K9 Thunder]], aligning with Finland and Norway to enhance interoperability and logistics within the Nordic defense cooperation.<ref>https://www.dn.se/sverige/archer-racker-inte-armen-vill-kopa-artilleri-pa-larvfotter/</ref>

